	<dd><a name="comment_1719" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Vickie Mann</strong> replies:</em> The chartists fought for universal manhood suffrage. The suffragetes fought and died for votes for women.<br />Not voting does not frighten anyone. It just enables the party who can rely on their support to get an easy ride. Vote tactically and mobilise.</p> <p>Don't take your vote for granted, it was hard won. </p> <p></p>
	<small>
	written 23rd Apr 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=114&amp;commentid=1719">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_3055" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>A Teacher</strong> replies:</em> As a teacher i also want some democracy in my classes so i ask my students for feedback (directly or indirectly) from time to time. But in some classrooms students want to talk 'how to do classes' all the time, many in order to 'not to do anything else'. </p> <p>Four years seems to be a reasonable period, though many modern major political and economical decisions take more than that. Many people think that Blair's government did it wrong and have retired its support, but perhaps not voting has resulted in a Blair's victory.</p> <p>Democracy improves learning to use (and using) the 'gears' that democracy itself has foreseen, before others distort the reality and try to force a bad use for its own interest. Voting is just only one of these gears ...</p>
	<small>
	written 6th May 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=114&amp;commentid=3055">abusive?</a>
